# NEVER Use MapFallbackToFile

## Prohibition

**NEVER add `MapFallbackToFile`, `MapFallback`, or any SPA-style catch-all fallback** to this application.

This is a **multi-page application** with separate HTML files (index.html, log-search.html, job-status.html, etc.). It is **NOT** a Single-Page Application (SPA). There is no client-side router.

## Why This Exists

`MapFallbackToFile("index.html")` was repeatedly added to `Program.cs` by AI agents following outdated rules, causing **all CSS, JS, and images to break** every time the app was deployed. This happened for 10+ days before the root cause was found.

## Technical Root Cause

All FK apps run as **IIS virtual applications** (e.g., `/GenericLogHandler`). HTML uses relative paths for CSS/JS:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/dashboard.css">
```

IIS automatically redirects `/GenericLogHandler` → `/GenericLogHandler/` (302) to ensure relative paths resolve correctly. `MapFallbackToFile` intercepts this request and returns `index.html` with 200 OK instead, preventing the redirect. The browser URL stays without trailing slash, and every relative CSS/JS path resolves to the wrong location.

Full explanation with Mermaid diagrams: `Docs/CSS-Loading-Flow.md`

## Correct Static File Configuration

```csharp
app.UseDefaultFiles();    // Rewrites / → /index.html
app.UseStaticFiles();     // Serves wwwroot/* files
// That's it. No fallback. No catch-all.
```

## What To Do Instead

- Need a new page? Create a new `.html` file in `wwwroot/` and link to it.
- Need a 404 page? Use `app.UseStatusCodePages()` or `app.UseStatusCodePagesWithReExecute()`.
- Need an API catch-all? Use `app.MapFallback()` with a controller action that returns proper HTTP status codes.

## Applies To All FK Apps

This rule applies to **all** FK web applications deployed as IIS virtual applications:
GenericLogHandler, DocView, ServerMonitorDashboard, AutoDocJson, DedgeAuth.
